title: 'Key & Peele' star Keegan-Michael Key to lead Penn State homecoming parade
text:
'Key & Peele' star Keegan-Michael Key to lead Penn State homecoming parade UPDATED 5:07 PM EDT Oct 08, 2015 
Keegan-Michael Key played "Luther," the anger translator for President Obama, at the White House Correspondents Dinner. Photos 
“What Just Happened”: There were a lot of jokes at the annual White House Correspondents Dinner Saturday night, but Keegan-Michael Key’s role as the President’s Anger Translator Luther stole the show. The “Key & Peele” character was plenty angry for the President until Obama himself started getting mad. 
Penn State University is bringing alumnus Keegan-Michael Key to serve as the school's homecoming grand marshal this week. Obama Gets Angry at White House Correspondents Dinner 
“What Just Happened”: There were a lot of jokes at the annual White House Correspondents Dinner Saturday night, but Keegan-Michael Key’s role as the President’s Anger Translator Luther stole the show. The “Key & Peele” character was plenty angry for the President until Obama himself started getting mad. 
The Centre Daily Times reports the 44-year-old actor says he hopes to give back to the university where he received his Master of Fine Arts degree in 1996. Key says he was surprised when he was asked to be the grand marshal, citing other alumni who he says were more deserving. Key lives in Los Angeles and is known for being a part of the Comedy Central TV show "Key & Peele." Key will lead the homecoming parade Friday and then attend the football game against Indiana on Saturday. He says he wants to meet with students during his trip and urges them to choose majors they're passionate about. State College here we come. Cost wait for this weekend @GoPSUsports We Are. . .
